  "text": "ISSN 2345-0282 (online) http://jssidoi.org/jesi/ 2018 Volume 5 Number 4 (June) http://doi.org/10.9770/jesi.2018.5.4(6) However, innovation success often depends on specific conditions. For example, an analysis of financial performance that was carried out on firms in the semiconductor and pharmaceutical industries did not reveal any significant differences in performance between clustered and non-clustered firms at the beginning of their life cycle, while in later phases, non-clustered firms outperformed clustered firms [CITATION_1] . Also, research by Žižka (2017) revealed the effect of the duration of the cluster's existence on performance. It addressed the effect of a textile cluster on the financial performance of member organisations. Financial performance was assessed using economic added value. It was found that the efficiency of firms in the cluster increased over the 5-year period under review, both due to a technological shift of the efficiency frontier and due to an improvement in internal efficiency resulting from economies of scale.",
